05231nam a22007335i 9780814738221DE-B159720200608045044.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200608t20142014nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808147382217 a10.18574/97808147382212doi  a(DE-B1597)548027  a(OCoLC)861692527  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aJV7048b.N49 2016 7aSOC0260002bisacsh04a305.9069120949235222300aNew York and Amsterdam :bImmigration and the New Urban Landscape /cNancy Foner, Jan Rath, Jan Willem Duyvendak, Rogier van Reekum. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[2014] 4cÂ©2014  a1 online resource :b32 black and white illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction. New York and Amsterdam: Immigration and the New Urban Landscape -- t1. Immigration History and the Remaking of New York -- t2. To Amsterdam -- t3. Immigrants in New York City's Economy -- t4. From Amsterdamned to I Amsterdam -- t5. Nativism, Racism, and Immigration in New York City -- t6. Governing through Religion in Amsterdam -- t7. The Rise of Immigrant Influence in New York City Politics -- t8. Immigrant Political Engagement and Incorporation in Amsterdam -- t9. Immigrants, the Arts, and the "Second- Generation Advantage" in New York -- t10. Immigrant Youths' Contribution to Urban Culture in Amsterdam -- tAbout the Contributors -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aImmigration is dramatically changing major cities throughout the world. Nowhere is this more so than in New York City and Amsterdam, which, after decades of large-scale immigration, now have populations that are more than a third foreign-born. These cities have had to deal with the challenge of incorporating hundreds of thousands of immigrants whose cultures, languages, religions, and racial backgrounds differ dramatically from those of many long-established residents. New York and Amsterdam brings together a distinguished and interdisciplinary group of American and Dutch scholars to examine and compare the impact of immigration on two of the world's largest urban centers. The original essays in this volume discuss how immigration has affected social, political, and economic structures, cultural patterns, and intergroup relations in the two cities, investigating how the particular, and changing, urban contexts of New York City and Amsterdam have shaped immigrant and second generation experiences. Despite many parallels between New York and Amsterdam, the differences stand out, and juxtaposing essays on immigration in the two cities helps to illuminate the essential issues that today's immigrants and their children confront. Organized around five main themes, this book offers an in-depth view of the impact of immigration as it affects particular places, with specific histories, institutions, and immigrant populations. New York and Amsterdam profoundly contributes to our broader understanding of the transformations wrought by immigration and the dynamics of urban change, providing new insights into how-and why- immigration's effects differ on the two sides of the Atlantic.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 08. Jun 2020) 0aCultural pluralismxNetherlandsxAmsterdam. 0aCultural pluralismxNew York (State)xNew York. 0aCultural pluralismzNetherlandszAmsterdam. 0aCultural pluralismzNew York (State)zNew York. 0aImmigrantsxNetherlandsxAmsterdam. 0aImmigrantsxNew York (State)xNew York. 0aImmigrantszNetherlandszAmsterdam. 0aImmigrantszNew York (State)zNew York. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh1 aDuyvendak, Jan Willem, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFoner, Nancy, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc